references: Utility measures for synthetic data are determined by the performance of synthetic data for any given task, such as classification or regression. Fidelity refers to the statistical similarity between real and its corresponding synthetic data. This encompasses aspects like the distribution of features across both datasets. Jordon et al. states that fidelity is often considered alongside utility [25]. In our benchmarking evaluation, we therefore considered Fidelity measures under Utility. In the evaluation context, Privacy is a measure that quantifies the amount of information about the original data revealed by its corresponding synthetic data. Table 2 provides a brief overview of the evaluation measures used.

TabDDPM and NextConvGeN preserve distributions of both continuous and categorical features in synthetic data:
We compared continuous feature distributions in real and synthetic data by comparing average p-values across the features by Student’s t-test (refer to Table 3). A high p-value (greater than the significance level of 0.050.050.05) indicates similarity between the distributions. As shown in Table 3, the results reveal that for all datasets, TVAE and CTAB-GAN+ yield p-values greater than 0.050.050.05, suggesting that the synthetic continuous feature distributions closely resemble the real ones. However, due to mode collapse, we could not sample enough of some datasets to maintain the cardinality of the target variable. The TabDDPM model produces a p-value less than 0.050.050.05 for only one dataset. Overall, TVAE, CTAB-GAN+, and TabDDPM demonstrate similarities between the synthetic and original continuous features. In the case of NextConvGeN, CTGAN, and CTAB-GAN, we find p-values above the 0.050.050.05 threshold for six, five, and four datasets, respectively. Notably, NextConvGeN yields higher p-values for most datasets. Consequently, we can infer that, after TVAE, CTAB-GAN+, and TabDDPM, the NextConvGeN model generates synthetic samples with indistinguishable sample means from the original samples.

references: Categorical features probability distributions across the synthetic and real data were compared using KL divergence, and the findings are shown in Table 4. A KL divergence score of zero signifies that the distributions are identical. In contrast, higher scores indicate that the distributions are different. TabDDPM proves to be the best-performing model, followed by NextConvGeN, generating synthetic data with categorical features probability distributions that are closer to the real data. However, one can observe that there are only small differences in the performances of the TabDDPM and NextConvGeN models, and they are quite comparable in terms of performance. TVAE, CTGAN, and CTAB-GAN models achieved higher KL divergence scores consistently compared to other models, indicating that the categorical probability distributions are not well preserved. On the other hand, CTAB-GAN+ produces a smaller KL divergence score compared to other GAN-based models and TVAE. Overall, the findings show that TabDDPM and NextConvGeN are suitable for generating synthetic categorical variables with similar probability distributions in real data.

Synthetic data from TabDDPM preserves the distribution of clusters in real data:
Table 5 shows the log cluster values for various generative models across ten publicly available data sets. This metric measures how similar the distribution of clusters is across real and synthetic data. A higher magnitude for this measure would indicate a similar distribution of clusters in real and synthetic. As per Table 5, TabDDPM produces higher log cluster measures for five of the ten benchmarking datasets, which is superior to any other model. This indicates that the synthetic data generated by TabDDPM follows a similar cluster distribution as that of real data. However, the performance of NextConvGeN is comparable to TabDDPM, with the second highest average magnitude of the log-cluster metric. This shows that the distribution of clusters can be better retained in synthetic data by the models TabDDPM and NextConvGeN.

Classifiers trained on real data and NextConvGeN, TabDDPM synthetic data shows similar performance:
Table 6 compares the absolute cross-validation difference between the classifiers trained on real and synthetic data. The expected cross-validation difference is smaller when the synthetic data is similar to real data. We observe that out of ten benchmarking datasets, the NextConvGeN and TabDDPM model outperforms other synthetic data generation models for three datasets. The results indicate that even powerful classifiers like gradient boosting perform similarly when trained on synthetic data (generated by NextConvGeN or TabDDPM) and original data separately. On the other hand, the results of TVAE, CTGAN, CTAB-GAN, and CTAB-GAN+ show more considerable differences for most small clinical datasets compared to NextConvGeN and TabDDPM, indicating that these models are more suited for large datasets.

In Table 6, notice the absolute five-fold cross-validation performance difference between the gradient descent classifier trained on real and synthetic data. For the CTGAN and CTAB-GAN models, the difference is more than ten percent for more than fifty percent of the datasets. There is no objective measure in the literature that comments on the effect of such difference once these synthetic data generation strategies are applied to practical, real-life scenarios. More than a ten percent difference on more than half the datasets intuitively translates to poorly performing models. However, if we focus too much on making the synthetic data similar enough to the real data, we automatically compromise on privacy. Once the data distribution of the synthetic data is too similar to that of the real data, it is easier to track the real data back from the synthetic data (reidentification risk). This is reflected in our results. We observe that TabDDPM and NextConvGeN models perform worse than CTGAN and CTAB-GAN regarding privacy measures. Therefore, our results reflect the utility-privacy dilemma.

references: Assessment of predictive consistency of classifiers trained on synthetic data on unseen data: To assess the comparability of classifiers trained on real and synthetic data, we evaluate their ability to perform on unseen real data (holdout data). To accomplish this, we compute the absolute difference in performance on holdout data between the classifiers trained on real and synthetic data, as detailed in Table 7. As the difference gets closer to zero, it indicates that the classifiers trained on real and synthetic data are similar, as reflected by an equivalent F1 score when tested on holdout data. The results in the table demonstrate that NextConvGeN, TabDDPM, and CTAB-GAN are comparable by slight differences in the three datasets. However, the TVAE, CTGAN, and CTAB-GAN+ model performs better in two of ten benchmark datasets. It is noteworthy that all models except TVAE show zero absolute difference in the case of lung cancer data. We cannot conclusively say from the results whether a particular synthetic data generation model has an edge over the others.

references: The ability of convex space learning to generate synthetic data with high utility: In the context of synthetic data generation, the propensity score is the most commonly used utility measure for evaluating synthetic data [31, 32, 33]. The value for this measure lies between 00 and 0.250.250.25. If the value is towards 00, then it indicates two datasets (real and synthetic) are identical, and the value towards 0.250.250.25 shows they are different [30]. Table 8 presents the results of propensity scores for various models across the benchmarking dataset. From the table, we can observe that NextConvGeN has a propensity score close to zero, suggesting that it is challenging for the machine learning classifiers to differentiate between real and NextConvGeN generated synthetic data. This demonstrates that the convex space learning technique can generate synthetic samples for small tabular clinical data similar to the original data.
